Sure thing! Here's a simple "Hello, World!" program in C:
```
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
  printf("Hello, World!\n");
  return 0;
}
```
To compile and run this program, save it to a file called `hello.c`, then run the command `gcc hello.c -o hello` in the terminal. This will create an executable file called `hello`. You can then run the program by typing `./hello` in the terminal.

The program includes a header file called `stdio.h`, which contains declarations for standard input/output functions. The `printf` function is used to print the string "Hello, World!" to the standard output. The `return 0` statement at the end of the `main` function indicates that the program executed successfully.
